The materials date from 1952-83.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Washington Theater Club was formed in 1957 to fill a perceived cultural void; to present good drama, away from Broadway; to speak out in plays of consequence; to present new ideas, new forms, and quality theater, which could be enjoyed and performed without racial barriers. The initial days of the Washington Theater Club were financially complex. John Wentworth had acquired a carriage house at 1632 0 St. N.W. in Georgetown, which had the essential space for a small intimate theater, with possible expansion potential. Zoning required that any theater venture be designated a private club. Even with a heavy input of money, Wentworth could not finance a professional theater and the building. The Washington Drama Center was organized to rent the building and pay for alterations to convert the space to a theater; and thereafter to provide professional theater, a drama school, and other activities.

Theater Venture I and Theater Venture II were developed to solicit funding to finance productions in 1960 and 1961. The Dramatic Arts Society of the District of Columbia was created to conduct a school and to produce and sponsor theatrical productions as a non-profit corporation, eligible to receive foundation and community support. The Washington Theater Club functioned with these support groups from 1957 to 1963, when it was incorporated as a non-profit theater and could stand alone. The designation "club" was necessary because of zoning problems resulting from the Club's location in a residential neighborhood adjacent to a church. The theater was, in actual fact, open to all with payment of nominal dues of $1.00.

As evidence of its growing success, the Washington Theater Club acquired a second location at 23rd and L Streets, N.W., which opened in 1970. The records of the Washington Theater Club reflect the progress of a regional theater from a small intimate dramatic venture to a full-fledged, highly acclaimed professional dramatic force operating at two locations, capable of successfully launching plays which had failed on Broadway, and effective in introducing new productions, new playwrights, and new performers. So successful was the club under the direction of Davey Marlin-Jones, that on April 11, 1969, it became the first theater in Washington to win the coveted Margo Jones award for persistence in a continuing program of new play productions. Its accomplishments included the production of ten world premieres, four American premieres, thirty Washington premieres, and the introduction of sixty-four writers new to area audiences.

Programs developed for dark Monday nights included staged readings of new plays to test feasibility for full production. Other programs included concerts by the Theater Chamber Players, who later became resident at the Kennedy Center, separate series of jazz concerts, dance, mime, and international events, as well as a showcase gallery in the lobby. The existing drama school, begun under the direction of the Wentworths, continued as a club activity to provide training for all ages and interaction with professional performers and directors. Like the theater production staff, Hazel Wentworth was motivated to expand the influence of the school to the disadvantaged, with outreach to Anacostia, a joint grant with Bowie State College, in-service training for college students on the east coast, and touring theater in the public schools and parks.

Like other performing arts groups which flourished in the sixties but did not survive the seventies, the Theater Club came to an end in 1974. Despite cash flow difficulties and a reliance on modestly-paid and volunteer staff, the Washington Theater Club was noted for its expansion into new areas and dramatic excellence from its modest inception in a 142-seat theater space to its two-house status with more than 9,000 subscribers.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains correspondence, scripts, resumes, programs, administrative records, financial documents, photographs, art work, and audio cassettes. The materials date from 1952-83. These records provide insight into many facets of theater management. There are extensive files of resumes for acting and support staff, of constant communication with Actors' Equity, League of Resident Theaters, and similar groups, materials related to funding and grant support, royalty negotiations, audition records, screening in large cities, and subscription and box office records. The collection also contains records related to the Board of Trustees.

Please note: the folder numbering is a mixture of an original numbering scheme and those a newer scheme designed by Special Collection staff. For this reason there may be times when the folder numbers may appear run consecutively. These numbers are simply used as a location guide and no material is missing and the material is in the correct order.
Hazel H. Wentworth, Executive Director and co-founder of the Washington Theater Club, donated these records in 1979.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: Production files, Administrative files, General accounting, and Artwork, audio tapes, and record albums

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, flyers, brochures, newspaper and magazine articles, news releases, advertisements, programs, opening night lists, production staff worksheets, scripts, applications, and resumes. The material dates from 1960-79 with the bulk of the material falling within 1960-74.

The first segment of the Production series contains Productions 1 to 90, arranged chronologically by numbered production. Within each file there are divisions with the following headings: programs, newspaper and magazines, advertisements, news releases, flyers and brochures, promotion- administrative, WTC extended (refers to productions whose runs were extended), production staff worksheets, opening night lists, art work, and cast background information.

Non-Equity Productions 1 to 10 are filed with the same order strategy as the other major productions. Thereafter, Scripts 1 to 183 are arranged alphabetically by author, or by title, if no author is available. The scripts are of various types: some represent major productions; some were offered as Monday night readings; and many were never produced. Production numbers are provided as a cross reference to production files whenever possible.

Correspondence and conclusions related to Script Reading for the years 1963-70 are filed after the Scripts section. Later script analysis was done by the Board of Trustees rather than the theater staff, and their efforts are filed with the Board materials under Playreading Committee. The next segment of the Production Series contains applications and resumes of actors, actresses, technical staff, managers, and directors. At the beginning of this segment are index files; one small collection on 3 x 5 cards with dates ranging from October 1972 to 1973, sorted by potential casting categories. Some similar cards of both types are scattered through the resume folders. In addition, ratings A - C, and/or numbers appear on some cards and resumes (presumably part of the organized audition process), as well as candid comments, negative and positive, to provide guidance in future casting.

Applications and resumes with supporting documentation have been placed in one comprehensive alphabetical order, with papers for each application in the following order: resume; photograph; material such as brochures, press releases, letters of recommendation, and educational credentials; and correspondence. Multiple resumes for the same individual are arranged chronologically, to the extent possible with existing evidence.

Within this series there were originally many folders grouped together and designated as "active", which, as directors changed, became "inactive." There were also resumes in mailing envelopes, never opened, as well as a few scripts, query letters, and personal correspondence, now relocated in appropriate series. Most files were not dated. For potential research value, original folders with significant headings have been retained, with a listing of prior contents on the folder or sheet of yellow paper which identified, them, and are arranged alphabetically at the end of the Resume file.

The segment of the collection designated Special Events includes improvisational evenings, play productions by and for the Theater Club, staged readings of new plays, concerts by special groups, five years of performances by the Theater Chamber Players (a group which later became the resident company at the Kennedy Center), jazz concerts, dance programs, mime, and other special events. Arrangement within each folder conforms to the pattern established in the initial production series. Most of these events were presented on dark Monday evenings when the theater was not otherwise in use. Additional special productions will be found under Children's Theater Productions. The Children's Theater Production section contains shows produced in the Washington Theater Club training programs for children and teenagers, professional performances for young and family audiences (sponsored by the Theater Club), community outreach programs, and administrative material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, minutes, correspondence, reports, and financial documents. The material dates from 1952-83 with the bulk of the documents falling between 1957-74.

The Administrative Series begins with folders dealing with John Wentworth's work with children's shOws prior to the founding of the Washington Drama Center in 1957 through the life and closing of the Washington Theater Club and the establishment of an Archive. The concept of the history file, established by earlier workers, may prove useful, although it is not completely developed and involves some duplication of material filed elsewhere. Included with the history file are biographical material on key personnel and assorted photographs.

The next division includes official documents concerning the origin and development of the Theater Club and its support groups, as well as reports of membership meetings, which expand the scope of the historical folders. Speakers and performers at membership meetings include Blanche Yurka on November 21, 1960 and Viveca Lindfors on September 13, 1971.

Board of Trustees minutes and correspondence are arranged chronologically and include reports and papers relating to management, monetary support, and promotion of the Theater Club, with folders inserted to cover major issues, such as selecting and planning the expanded theater space. Records of planning, budgeting, and management of bank accounts and loans are filed here when they relate to the Board agenda. Part of the committee structure was a Playreading Committee, 1971-74, formed when the Board decided to assume a role in the selection of scripts for production. Some significant events, such as they Margo Jones award, and significant fund-raising events, are located under Board of Trustees Promotion. There is also a folder designated Successful Alumni.

The Public Relations segment is organized chronologically under the following headings: promotion, subscriptions (with occasional sub-headings), box office, correspondence, and staff communication. Promotion of a season or more than one show is located in this segment. There is no uniform pattern of fiscal years. New employees did not necessarily understand existing practice. When material is arranged by fiscal year, it is assumed that fiscal years ended in August until 1964-65. Thereafter the pattern is: September to September 1964-65, October to September 1965-69, October to August 1969-70, and September to August 1970-71 and thereafter. Master records of subscriptions are also located in the Administrative Series. The section under funding includes analysis of foundation records, followed by interaction with specific foundations, arranged chronologically by the date of the first successful contact. The folder Brookdale Foundation includes negotiations aimed at naming the theater or school for Pat Nixon. A folder for other appeals to foundations is followed by chronological folders for Fund Raising and Contributions, as well as the 1969-71 Capital Fund Drive.

The records of correspondence and reports made to Actors' Equity extend from 1959-74. There is one folder for the D.C. Federation of Musicians, and one for the Society of Stage Directors and Choreographers. Interaction with associations and conferences is reflected in files from 1962-73. The folder under United Performing Arts of Washington, 1966-72, reveals the continuing support of Joan Kennedy and Lynda Bird Johnson. The Royalties section includes all types of productions within each year, listed by title, with identifying number, for ease in referring back to the actual performance, and for a partial impression of the multiple activities occurring in overlapping periods.

In the Theater Training School records, generalized administration is followed by specific classes, arranged alphabetically under Adult Training, Junior Stage, and Teenage Theater, with a chronological sequence under each class title. Following the basic classes there is extensive material on teenage theater designed to build confidence and personality growth. Grants to support these activities are filed by date within the Training School material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains ledgers, expenditures, invoices, checks, receipts, pretty cash records, and insurance. The material dates from 1957-1974.

These records divided into either calendar or fiscal year. The order for the material is Budget, then Ledger, followed by the Expenditures section in an imposed classified order containing invoices, receipts, and petty cash records, under the following headings: building supplies and maintenance, production and office, promotion, subscriptions, box office, and box office for specific productions. Insurance records are also filed in this series. Multiple bank accounts are filed in chronological order. Checks have been retained to supplement the accounting records. The last section of the General Accounts Series contains tax records, and includes Federal, D.C., Maryland, and Virginia taxes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains artwork, audio tapes, and record albums. The material dates from 1960-70.

These materials consisting of unidentified material, duplicates of artwork, and individual items that did not fit into the other series. There are also audio tapes, which are in no established order, and phonograph records. The records are mostly 33 1/3 RPM albums, arranged roughly by size and country of origin. The music ranges from popular tunes to folk songs.
